[[ja:冠位・位階制度の変遷]]
'''Transition of Ranks and Court Titles''' (冠位・位階制度の変遷, Kan’i Ikai Seido no Hensen) explains the historical development of the rank and [[court rank|title system]] in [[Japan]].

The first unified system of ranks for government officials in Japan was introduced with the [[Twelve Cap Ranks]] (冠位十二階, Kan’i Jūnikai) in the 11th year of [[Empress Suiko]]'s reign (603 CE). With the establishment of the [[Taihō Code]] (大宝律令, Taihō Ritsuryō) in the first year of the [[Taihō era]] (701 CE), a comprehensive system matching ranks with [[official titles]] (官位相当制, Kan’i Sōtōsei) was formalized. Although the rank system changed significantly as the [[Ritsuryō system]] declined, the basic structure remained intact. During the [[Meiji Restoration]], the traditional rank and title systems were abolished and replaced with new ones. The [[Decorations Bureau]] (叙位条例, Joki Jōrei) enacted in Meiji 20 (1887) separated ranks from official titles, making them primarily a system of [[honor]]. Further reforms in the [[Taishō era]] with the [[Rank System Ordinance]] (位階令, Ikai Rei) in Taishō 15 (1926) refined the honorary nature of the system. Even after the enactment of the [[Constitution of Japan]], ranks were conferred under this ordinance.

== Cap Rank Systems ==
=== Twelve Cap Ranks ===
{{Main|Twelve Cap Ranks}}
In the 11th year of [[Empress Suiko]] (603 CE), the Twelve Cap Ranks were established. Government officials were ranked into 12 caps: [[Daitoku|Great Virtue]], [[Shōtoku|Small Virtue]], [[Dainin|Great Humanity]], [[Shōnin|Small Humanity]], [[Dairei|Great Propriety]], [[Shōrei|Small Propriety]], [[Daishin|Great Faith]], [[Shōshin|Small Faith]], [[Daigi|Great Righteousness]], [[Shōgi|Small Righteousness]], [[Daichi|Great Wisdom]], and [[Shōchi|Small Wisdom]]. Each cap was distinguished by its color, but the exact colors are not documented.

=== Thirteen Cap Ranks ===
{{Main|Thirteen Cap Ranks}}
In [[Taika]] 3 (647 CE), the system was revised into Thirteen Cap Ranks and implemented the following year. This system integrated the [[Purple Cap]], previously outside the ranking system, and introduced six additional ranks above the original twelve: [[Ōshoku|Great Woven]] and [[Shōshoku|Small Woven]], [[Ōshū|Great Embroidered]] and [[Shōshū|Small Embroidered]], and [[Ōshi|Great Purple]] and [[Shōshi|Small Purple]]. Colors and materials were defined, ranging from [[purple]] to [[crimson]], [[blue]], and [[green]].

=== Nineteen Cap Ranks ===
{{Main|Nineteen Cap Ranks}}
Two years after its introduction, the Thirteen Cap Ranks were revised to include new ranks between [[Ōhana|Great Flower]] and [[Shōotsu|Small乙]], creating the Nineteen Cap Ranks. The structure was implemented in [[Taika]] 5 (649 CE).

=== Twenty-Six Cap Ranks ===
{{Main|Twenty-Six Cap Ranks}}
In [[Emperor Tenji]]'s 3rd year (664 CE), the system expanded to Twenty-Six Cap Ranks. The [[Shōshū|Embroidered Cap]] was renamed [[Nuikan|Sewn Cap]], and the [[Hana|Flower Cap]] became the [[Kin|Brocade Cap]]. Additionally, each lower rank from [[Ōkin|Great Brocade]] to [[Shōotsu|Small乙]] was divided into upper, middle, and lower ranks.

=== Forty-Eight Cap Ranks ===
In the 14th year of [[Emperor Tenmu]] (685 CE), the Forty-Eight Cap Ranks were introduced.<ref>''Nihon Shoki,'' Emperor Tenmu, 14th year, 1st month, 丁卯条.</ref> This coincided with the establishment of the [[Eight House Names]] (八色の姓, Hasshiki no Kabane) in the previous year. The Forty-Eight Ranks separated the [[royal family]] (親王) into their own Twelve Cap Ranks distinct from [[subjects]] (諸臣). Colors were assigned for ceremonial robes, ranging from [[vermilion]], [[purple]], [[green]], to [[blue]]. These ranks persisted until the [[Taihō Ritsuryō]] was implemented.

{{-}}

== Taihō Code and Rank System ==
{{Main|Rank and Court Title System}}
With the establishment of the [[Taihō Code]] in [[Taihō]] 1 (701 CE), the rank system transitioned to a simplified format with 30 ranks based on the Forty-Eight Cap Ranks. Titles for [[royals]] (親王) ranged from [[Ippon|First Rank]] to [[Yonhon|Fourth Rank]]. Non-royal officials were assigned from [[Shōichi|Senior First Rank]] to [[Jūgo|Junior Fifth Rank]]. External officials were granted ranks below Fifth Rank, known as [[Gaikai|Outer Ranks]], awarded for contributions to the court. Military honors were conferred through a separate [[Order of Merit]] (十二等).

{{-}}

== Modern Rank System ==
In the [[Meiji era]], the [[Daijōkan]] system redefined ranks, and the [[Kan’on]] structure of 15 grades replaced traditional ranks. Though ranks continued as honorary distinctions, they became disconnected from official titles.

=== Ordinances ===
* The [[Decoration Bureau Ordinance]] (1887 CE) emphasized ranks as honors, reducing the total to 16.
* The [[Rank System Ordinance]] (1926 CE) solidified the honorary system. Since [[1946 CE]], ranks have been awarded posthumously only.

== Notes ==
{{reflist}}

== Related Topics ==
