In the 14th year of {{ill|Emperor Tenmu|ja|Emperor Tenmu|1=Emperor Tenmu|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (685 CE), the [[Forty-Eight-Level Cap and Rank System]] was introduced. The Ranks were grouped into categories, with [[royal family]] members Ranked above the [[臣]] (vassals). [[Color-coded clothing]] indicated Rank hierarchy. This system lasted until the [[Taihō Code]].

== Modern Rank Systems ==
=== Meiji Period ===
During the Meiji Restoration, traditional Rank systems were abolished and replaced with modernized structures. The {{ill|Order of Merit|ja|叙位条例|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (1887) separated Ranks from official positions, making them symbolic honors.

=== Order of Rank ===
In 1926, the {{ill|Order of Rank|ja|位階令|qq=draft|qq=draft}} codified the system into a posthumous honorary structure. Despite changes in Japan's [[Constitution]], the Rank system remains a tool of historical recognition.

