'''Transitions of the Kani and Ikai Systems''' (冠位・位階制度の変遷) explains the transitions in the {{ill|Rank and Grade|ja|冠位|1=Transition of Crown and Court Ranks|lt=Crown Rank|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Rank and Grade|13=User:Immanuelle/Transition of Crown and Court Ranks|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 冠位・位階制度の変遷}} system in [[Japan]].
The first unified system to Rank [[officials]] in Japan was established in the 11th year of [[:en:Empress Suiko|Empress Suiko]] (603 CE) with the enactment of the [[:en:Twelve Level Cap and Rank System|Twelve Level Cap and Rank System]]. In the first year of the [[:en:Taiho|Taihō era]] (701 CE), the [[:en:Taihō Code|Taihō Code]] introduced the [[:en:List of Japanese court ranks, positions and hereditary titles|Kan'i sōtō system]], aligning Ranks and [[official positions]]. Although the [[:en:Ritsuryō|Ritsuryō system]] later declined, and the significance of Ranks changed, the format of Ranks itself saw little alteration. With the [[Meiji Restoration]], the traditional Rank and position system was abolished, and a new Rank system was established. The {{ill|Order of Merit|ja|叙位条例|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Order of Merit|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} (Imperial Ordinance No. 10 of 1887) severed the link between Ranks and positions, making the system solely for [[:en:commendation|commendation]]. Further refinement occurred under the {{ill|Order of Rank|ja|位階令|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Order of Rank|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 位階}} (Imperial Ordinance No. 325 of 1926), which solidified the system as one of recognition. Even after the enactment of the [[:en:Constitution of Japan|Constitution of Japan]], the Order of Rank continues to be used for posthumous recognition.
